# Mandatory React Rules

## Statement

- All React components MUST have typed props.
- If a props type will be reused, it MUST be defined in a `types` file in the same directory. If it will not be reused, it MUST be defined in the component file.
- Every component MUST be a function component.
- It is prohibited to use `React.FC`.
- State and effects MUST be used carefully. Unnecessary state, derived state, incorrect dependencies, and unscoped side effects are prohibited.
- `useMemo` and `useCallback` MUST be used only when applicable, such as to protect expensive derived values or preserve referential stability when it matters. Unnecessary memoization is discouraged.

## Rationale

Using typed props and consistent function components makes React code easier to read, safer to change, and simpler to maintain. Keeping reusable types colocated and one-off types local helps preserve clarity without scattering definitions unnecessarily. Avoiding `React.FC` keeps component signatures explicit and prevents implicit behavior that is not needed.

Being careful with state and effects improves render predictability and reduces bugs caused by stale values, redundant state, and side effects that run outside their intended scope. Using `useMemo` and `useCallback` only when they provide a clear benefit helps balance performance with readability and avoids adding accidental complexity to the component tree.
